    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically a partnership between the two materials to handle different types of physical stress. but what happens if the rebar wasn't there? like, if a foundation just relies on the concrete alone, what's the specific mechanism that causes it to fail when it's under tension? does the concrete just snap or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the rebar were absent, the concrete foundation would fail catastrophically under tensile stress, which is a situation where it's being pulled apart. Instead of a clean \"snap,\" it would typically exhibit cracking, and these cracks would propagate until the material can no longer bear the load. The concrete's failure mechanism under tension is essentially brittle fracture; it doesn't bend much before it breaks, unlike steel.\n\nThis is why the rebar is so vital; it acts as the internal skeleton, absorbing those tensile forces that the concrete simply cannot manage on its own. Without it, the foundation would be susceptible to things like bending moments or differential settling, which introduce pulling forces. In essence, the concrete would just crumble apart under the strain.",
      "source": "target",
